{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"I always wanted to become\na walking laboratory of social engagement:"},{"time":6313,"text":"to resonate other people's feelings,\nthoughts, intentions, motivations,"},{"time":11707,"text":"in the act of being with them."},{"time":14999,"text":"As a scientist, I always wanted\nto measure that resonance,"},{"time":20776,"text":"that sense of the other\nthat happens so quickly,"},{"time":23418,"text":"in the blink of an eye."},{"time":25682,"text":"We intuit other people's feelings;"},{"time":28032,"text":"we know the meaning of their actions\neven before they happen."},{"time":31959,"text":"We're always in this stance"},{"time":33729,"text":"of being the object\nof somebody else's subjectivity."},{"time":36835,"text":"We do that all the time.\nWe just can't shake it off."},{"time":40025,"text":"It's so important that the very tools\nwe use to understand ourselves,"},{"time":43748,"text":"to understand the world around us,"},{"time":45599,"text":"are shaped by that stance."},{"time":48226,"text":"We are social to the core."}]},{"cues":[{"time":51572,"text":"So my journey in autism really started"},{"time":54047,"text":"when I lived in a residential unit\nfor adults with autism."},{"time":58068,"text":"Most of those individuals\nhad spent most of their lives"},{"time":61183,"text":"in long-stay hospitals."},{"time":62692,"text":"This is a long time ago."},{"time":65021,"text":"And for them, autism was devastating."},{"time":69395,"text":"They had profound\nintellectual disabilities."},{"time":72558,"text":"They didn't talk."},{"time":74310,"text":"But most of all,"},{"time":76217,"text":"they were extraordinarily isolated\nfrom the world around them,"},{"time":81170,"text":"from their environment"},{"time":83031,"text":"and from the people."},{"time":85392,"text":"In fact, at the time,\nif you walked into a school"},{"time":88243,"text":"for individuals with autism,"},{"time":90055,"text":"you'd hear a lot of noise,"},{"time":92392,"text":"plenty of commotion, actions,\npeople doing things."},{"time":97730,"text":"But they're always doing\nthings by themselves."},{"time":101405,"text":"So they may be looking\nat a light in the ceiling,"},{"time":105527,"text":"or they may be isolated in the corner,"},{"time":108936,"text":"or they might be engaged\nin these repetitive movements,"},{"time":112495,"text":"in self-stimulatory movements\nthat led them nowhere."},{"time":116558,"text":"Extremely, extremely isolated."}]},{"cues":[{"time":120625,"text":"Well, now we know that autism\nis this disruption,"},{"time":126229,"text":"the disruption of this resonance\nthat I am telling you about."},{"time":129770,"text":"These are survival skills."},{"time":131728,"text":"These are survival skills\nthat we inherited"},{"time":134638,"text":"over many, many hundreds\nof thousands of years of evolution."}]},{"cues":[{"time":138845,"text":"You see, babies are born\nin a state of utter fragility."},{"time":144032,"text":"Without the caregiver,\nthey wouldn't survive,"},{"time":146185,"text":"so it stands to reason\nthat nature would endow them"},{"time":148715,"text":"with these mechanisms of survival."},{"time":152169,"text":"They orient to the caregiver."},{"time":154525,"text":"From the first days and weeks of life,"},{"time":157940,"text":"babies prefer to hear human sounds,"},{"time":160698,"text":"rather than just sounds\nin the environment."},{"time":162846,"text":"They prefer to look at people\nrather than at things,"},{"time":165347,"text":"and even as they're looking at people,\nthey look at people's eyes,"},{"time":169747,"text":"because the eye is the window\nto the other person's experiences,"},{"time":173979,"text":"so much so that they even prefer\nto look at people"},{"time":176461,"text":"who are looking at them\nrather than people who are looking away."},{"time":180525,"text":"Well, they orient to the caregiver."},{"time":183131,"text":"The caregiver seeks the baby."},{"time":185272,"text":"And it's out of this mutually\nreinforcing choreography"},{"time":189085,"text":"that a lot that is of importance\nto the emergence of mind --"},{"time":192904,"text":"the social mind, the social\nbrain -- depends on."}]},{"cues":[{"time":197587,"text":"We always think about autism"},{"time":200683,"text":"as something that happens\nlater on in life."},{"time":205347,"text":"It doesn't; it begins\nwith the beginning of life."},{"time":210901,"text":"As babies engage with caregivers,\nthey soon realize that, well,"},{"time":216520,"text":"there is something between the ears\nthat is very important --"},{"time":220666,"text":"it's invisible, you can't see it,\nbut it's really critical."},{"time":224849,"text":"And that thing is called attention."},{"time":226800,"text":"And they learn soon enough,"},{"time":228157,"text":"even before they can utter one word,"},{"time":230769,"text":"that they can take that attention\nand move somewhere"},{"time":234273,"text":"in order to get things they want."},{"time":237555,"text":"They also learn to follow\nother people's gazes,"},{"time":240679,"text":"because whatever people are looking at\nis what they are thinking about."},{"time":246704,"text":"And soon enough, they start to learn\nabout the meaning of things,"},{"time":250374,"text":"because when somebody\nis looking at something"},{"time":252771,"text":"or somebody is pointing at something,"},{"time":255013,"text":"they're not just getting\na directional cue."},{"time":257752,"text":"They are getting the other\nperson's meaning of that thing,"},{"time":261459,"text":"the attitude."},{"time":262693,"text":"And soon enough, they start\nbuilding this body of meanings,"},{"time":267488,"text":"but meanings that were acquired\nwithin the realm of social interaction."},{"time":272110,"text":"Those are meanings that are acquired"},{"time":274049,"text":"as part of their shared\nexperiences with others."}]},{"cues":[{"time":278086,"text":"Well, this is a 15-month-old little girl,"},{"time":285512,"text":"and she has autism."},{"time":288594,"text":"And I am coming so close to her\nthat I am maybe two inches from her face,"},{"time":294406,"text":"and she's quite oblivious to me."},{"time":296265,"text":"Imagine if I did that to you,\ncame two inches from your face."},{"time":299717,"text":"You'd do probably\ntwo things, wouldn't you?"},{"time":301946,"text":"You would recoil.\nYou would call the police."}]},{"cues":[{"time":304568,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":305766,"text":"You would do something,"},{"time":306943,"text":"because it's literally impossible\nto penetrate somebody's physical space"},{"time":311025,"text":"and not get that reaction."},{"time":312452,"text":"We do so, remember,\nintuitively, effortlessly."},{"time":315931,"text":"This is our body wisdom;"},{"time":317120,"text":"it's not something mediated\nby our language."},{"time":319342,"text":"Our body just knows that."},{"time":322269,"text":"And we've known that for a long time."}]},{"cues":[{"time":324661,"text":"And this is not something\nthat happens to humans only."},{"time":327600,"text":"It happens to some\nof our phyletic cousins,"},{"time":330824,"text":"because if you're a monkey,\nand you look at another monkey,"},{"time":334914,"text":"and that monkey has a higher\nhierarchy position than you,"},{"time":338932,"text":"and that is considered\nto be a signal or threat,"},{"time":342485,"text":"well, you are not going\nto be alive for long."},{"time":345365,"text":"So something that in other species\nare survival mechanisms,"},{"time":350221,"text":"without which they\nwouldn't basically live,"},{"time":353352,"text":"we bring into the context of human beings,"},{"time":355907,"text":"and this is what we need\nto simply act, socially."}]},{"cues":[{"time":360180,"text":"Now, she is oblivious to me\nand I'm so close to her,"},{"time":362973,"text":"and you think, maybe she can see you,"},{"time":364971,"text":"maybe she can hear you."},{"time":366506,"text":"Well, a few minutes later,"},{"time":368152,"text":"she goes to the corner of the room,"},{"time":370117,"text":"and she finds a tiny little piece\nof candy, an M&amp;M."},{"time":374859,"text":"So I could not attract her attention,"},{"time":379400,"text":"but something -- a thing -- did."},{"time":381930,"text":"Now, most of us make a big dichotomy"},{"time":384471,"text":"between the world of things\nand the world of people."},{"time":388882,"text":"Now, for this girl,\nthat division line is not so clear,"},{"time":393397,"text":"and the world of people\nis not attracting her"},{"time":396527,"text":"as much as we would like."},{"time":398010,"text":"Now, remember that we learn a great deal\nby sharing experiences."},{"time":402445,"text":"What she is doing right now\nis that her path of learning is diverging,"},{"time":408330,"text":"moment by moment,"},{"time":410095,"text":"as she is isolating herself\nfurther and further."},{"time":413913,"text":"So we feel sometimes\nthat the brain is deterministic,"},{"time":416879,"text":"the brain determines\nwho we're going to be."},{"time":419429,"text":"But, in fact, the brain\nalso becomes who we are,"},{"time":422241,"text":"and at the same time\nthat her behaviors are taking away"},{"time":426254,"text":"from the realm of social interaction,"},{"time":428440,"text":"this is what's happening with her mind,"},{"time":430489,"text":"and this is what's happening\nwith her brain."}]},{"cues":[{"time":435143,"text":"Well, autism is the most strongly\ngenetic condition"},{"time":440367,"text":"of all developmental disorders."},{"time":444461,"text":"And it's a brain disorder."},{"time":446695,"text":"It's a disorder that begins\nmuch prior to the time"},{"time":449948,"text":"that the child is born."},{"time":452217,"text":"We now know that there is a very\nbroad spectrum of autism."},{"time":456222,"text":"There are those individuals\nwho are profoundly intellectually disabled"},{"time":459715,"text":"but there are those that are gifted."},{"time":461696,"text":"There are those individuals\nwho don't talk at all;"},{"time":464114,"text":"there are those individuals\nwho talk too much."},{"time":466526,"text":"There are those individuals\nthat if you observe them in their school,"},{"time":470047,"text":"you see them running the periphery fence\nall the school day if you let them,"},{"time":473741,"text":"to those individuals\nwho cannot stop coming to you"},{"time":476126,"text":"and trying to engage you\nrepeatedly, relentlessly,"},{"time":479091,"text":"but often in an awkward fashion,"},{"time":482232,"text":"without that immediate resonance."}]},{"cues":[{"time":485812,"text":"Well, this is much more prevalent\nthan we thought at the time."},{"time":489582,"text":"When I started in this field,"},{"time":491017,"text":"we thought there were four individuals\nwith autism per 10,000 --"},{"time":494129,"text":"a very rare condition."},{"time":495861,"text":"Well, now we know it's more\nlike one in 100."},{"time":499957,"text":"There are millions of individuals\nwith autism all around us."}]},{"cues":[{"time":505216,"text":"The societal cost\nof this condition is huge,"},{"time":508585,"text":"in the US alone,\nmaybe 35 to 80 billion dollars."},{"time":511557,"text":"And you know what?"},{"time":512769,"text":"Most of those funds are associated\nwith adolescents and particularly adults"},{"time":517430,"text":"who are severely disabled,"},{"time":519205,"text":"individuals who need\nwraparound services --"},{"time":521390,"text":"services that are very, very intensive."},{"time":523670,"text":"And those services can cost in excess\nof 60,000 to 80,000 dollars a year."},{"time":528536,"text":"Those are individuals who did not\nbenefit from early treatment,"},{"time":532474,"text":"because now we know\nthat autism creates itself"},{"time":536636,"text":"as individuals diverge in that pathway\nof learning that I mentioned to you."},{"time":541200,"text":"Were we to be able\nto identify this condition"},{"time":543797,"text":"at an earlier point,\nand intervene and treat --"},{"time":547812,"text":"I can tell you, this has been probably\nsomething that has changed my life"},{"time":551890,"text":"in the past 10 years,"},{"time":553210,"text":"this notion that we can absolutely\nattenuate this condition."},{"time":558922,"text":"Also, we have a window of opportunity,"},{"time":561301,"text":"because the brain\nis malleable for just so long,"},{"time":564437,"text":"and that window of opportunity\nhappens in the first three years of life."},{"time":567974,"text":"It's not that that window\ncloses; it doesn't."},{"time":571621,"text":"But it diminishes considerably."},{"time":574899,"text":"And yet, the median age\nof diagnosis in this country"},{"time":578021,"text":"is still about five years,"},{"time":579957,"text":"and in disadvantaged populations,"},{"time":582076,"text":"the populations that don't have\naccess to clinical services,"},{"time":585229,"text":"rural populations, minorities,"},{"time":588338,"text":"the age of diagnosis is later still,"},{"time":591071,"text":"which is almost as if I were to tell you"},{"time":593120,"text":"that we are condemning those communities\nto have individuals with autism"},{"time":596911,"text":"whose condition is going\nto be more severe."},{"time":600162,"text":"So I feel that we have\na bioethical imperative."},{"time":603168,"text":"The science is there."},{"time":606025,"text":"But no science is of relevance"},{"time":608169,"text":"if it doesn't have an impact\non the community."},{"time":611727,"text":"And we just can't afford\nthat missed opportunity,"},{"time":614705,"text":"because children with autism\nbecome adults with autism."},{"time":618412,"text":"And we feel that those things we can do"},{"time":622440,"text":"for these children,\nfor those families, early on,"},{"time":624842,"text":"will have lifetime consequences --"},{"time":627043,"text":"for the child, for the family,\nand for the community at large."},{"time":631075,"text":"So this is our view of autism."}]},{"cues":[{"time":634145,"text":"There are over a hundred genes\nthat are associated with autism."},{"time":637491,"text":"In fact, we believe there are going to be"},{"time":639474,"text":"something between 300 and 600\ngenes associated with autism,"},{"time":643303,"text":"and genetic anomalies,\nmuch more than just genes."},{"time":647460,"text":"And we actually have\na bit of a question here,"},{"time":651644,"text":"because if there are so many\ndifferent causes of autism,"},{"time":654953,"text":"how do you go from those liabilities\nto the actual syndrome?"},{"time":659245,"text":"Because people like myself,"},{"time":661530,"text":"when we walk into a playroom,"},{"time":663791,"text":"we recognize a child as having autism."},{"time":666835,"text":"So how do you go from multiple causes"},{"time":669087,"text":"to a syndrome that has some homogeneity?"},{"time":672491,"text":"And the answer is what lies in between,"},{"time":675753,"text":"which is development."},{"time":677660,"text":"And in fact, we are very interested\nin those first two years of life,"},{"time":682457,"text":"because those liabilities\ndon't necessarily convert into autism."},{"time":686269,"text":"Autism creates itself."},{"time":688812,"text":"Were we to be able to intervene\nduring those years of life,"},{"time":693569,"text":"we might attenuate for some, and God\nknows, maybe even prevent for others."}]},{"cues":[{"time":699975,"text":"So how do we do that?"},{"time":701837,"text":"How do we enter that feeling of resonance,"},{"time":704753,"text":"how do we enter another person's being?"},{"time":709137,"text":"I remember when I interacted\nwith that 15-month-old,"},{"time":712276,"text":"the thing that came to my mind was,"},{"time":714438,"text":"\"How do you come into her world?"},{"time":717410,"text":"Is she thinking about me?\nIs she thinking about others?\""},{"time":721910,"text":"Well, it's hard to do that,"},{"time":724784,"text":"so we had to create the technologies."},{"time":726986,"text":"We had to basically step inside a body."},{"time":729479,"text":"We had to see the world through her eyes."}]},{"cues":[{"time":733192,"text":"And so in the past many years,"},{"time":735528,"text":"we've been building these new technologies"},{"time":737948,"text":"that are based on eye tracking."},{"time":739553,"text":"We can see, moment by moment,\nwhat children are engaging with."},{"time":746046,"text":"This is my colleague, Warren Jones,"},{"time":747834,"text":"with whom we've been building\nthese methods, these studies,"},{"time":751152,"text":"for the past 12 years."},{"time":752879,"text":"And you see there a happy five-month-old,"},{"time":756789,"text":"a five-month little boy\nwho is going to watch things"},{"time":761880,"text":"that are brought from his world:"},{"time":764596,"text":"his mom, the caregiver,"},{"time":766853,"text":"but also experiences that he would have\nwere he to be in his daycare."},{"time":771884,"text":"What we want is to embrace that world\nand bring it into our laboratory,"},{"time":775748,"text":"but in order for us to do that,"},{"time":777806,"text":"we had to create\nthese very sophisticated measures,"},{"time":782085,"text":"measures of how people, how little babies,"},{"time":785590,"text":"how newborns, engage\nwith the world, moment by moment."},{"time":790128,"text":"What is important and what is not."}]},{"cues":[{"time":793163,"text":"Well, we created those measures,"},{"time":795798,"text":"and here, what you see\nis what we call a funnel of attention."},{"time":799826,"text":"You're watching a video --"},{"time":801739,"text":"those frames are separated\nby about a second --"},{"time":804494,"text":"through the eyes of 35 typically\ndeveloping two-year-olds."},{"time":808837,"text":"And we freeze one frame,"},{"time":811908,"text":"and this is what the typical\nchildren are doing."},{"time":815020,"text":"In this scan pass, in green here,\nare two-year-olds with autism."},{"time":819461,"text":"So on that frame, the children\nwho are typical are watching this,"},{"time":826039,"text":"the emotion of expression\nof that little boy"},{"time":828588,"text":"as he's fighting a little bit\nwith the little girl."},{"time":831338,"text":"What are the children with autism doing?"},{"time":833399,"text":"They are focusing on the revolving door,"},{"time":837304,"text":"opening and shutting."},{"time":839542,"text":"Well, I can tell you that this divergence\nthat you're seeing here"},{"time":842915,"text":"doesn't happen only\nin our five-minute experiment."},{"time":845751,"text":"It happens moment by moment\nin their real lives,"},{"time":849820,"text":"and their minds are being formed\nand their brains are being specialized"},{"time":854077,"text":"in something other than what is happening\nwith their typical peers."}]},{"cues":[{"time":858807,"text":"Well, we took a construct\nfrom our pediatrician friends,"},{"time":865350,"text":"the concept of growth charts --"},{"time":866893,"text":"you know, when you take\na child to the pediatrician,"},{"time":869394,"text":"and you have physical height and weight."},{"time":873066,"text":"Well, we decided we were going\nto create growth charts"},{"time":876024,"text":"of social engagement."},{"time":878354,"text":"We sought children\nfrom the time they're born."},{"time":881574,"text":"What you see here on the x-axis"},{"time":884973,"text":"is two, three, four, five,\nsix months and nine,"},{"time":889182,"text":"until about the age of 24 months."},{"time":890969,"text":"This is the percent of their viewing time"},{"time":893764,"text":"that they're focusing on people's eyes,"},{"time":895699,"text":"and this is their growth chart."},{"time":898144,"text":"They start over here --\nthey love people's eyes --"},{"time":900641,"text":"and it remains quite stable."},{"time":903350,"text":"It sort of goes up a little bit\nin those initial months."},{"time":907319,"text":"Now, let's see what's happening\nwith babies who became autistic."},{"time":911771,"text":"It's something very different."},{"time":914004,"text":"It starts way up here,\nbut then it's a free fall."},{"time":917799,"text":"It's very much like they brought\ninto this world the reflex"},{"time":921694,"text":"that orients them to people,\nbut it has no traction."},{"time":925511,"text":"It's almost as if that stimulus -- you --"},{"time":928540,"text":"you're not exerting\ninfluence on what happens"},{"time":931554,"text":"as they navigate their daily lives."}]},{"cues":[{"time":935236,"text":"Now, we thought those data\nwere so powerful, in a way,"},{"time":942686,"text":"that we wanted to see what happened\nin the first six months of life,"},{"time":945960,"text":"because if you interact\nwith a two- and a three-month-old,"},{"time":949192,"text":"you'd be surprised\nby how social those babies are."},{"time":953513,"text":"And what we see\nin the first six months of life"},{"time":956394,"text":"is that those two groups\ncan be segregated very easily."},{"time":962159,"text":"And using these kinds\nof measures and many others,"},{"time":965300,"text":"what we found out\nis that our science could, in fact,"},{"time":968977,"text":"identify this condition early on."},{"time":971749,"text":"We didn't have to wait\nfor the behaviors of autism"},{"time":974934,"text":"to emerge in the second year of life."},{"time":978156,"text":"If we measured things that are,\nevolutionarily, highly conserved,"},{"time":982707,"text":"and developmentally very early-emerging --"},{"time":985054,"text":"things that are online\nfrom the first weeks of life --"},{"time":987755,"text":"we could push the detection of autism"},{"time":989741,"text":"all the way to those first months,"},{"time":992293,"text":"and that's what we are doing now."}]},{"cues":[{"time":996618,"text":"Now, we can create\nthe very best technologies"},{"time":999799,"text":"and the very best methods\nto identify the children,"},{"time":1003591,"text":"but this would be for naught\nif we didn't have an impact"},{"time":1006529,"text":"on what happens in their reality\nin the community."},{"time":1009680,"text":"Now we want those devices, of course,"},{"time":1011986,"text":"to be deployed by those\nwho are in the trenches --"},{"time":1014839,"text":"our colleagues, the primary care\nphysicians, who see every child --"},{"time":1020067,"text":"and we need to transform\nthose technologies"},{"time":1022454,"text":"into something that is going\nto add value to their practice,"},{"time":1025480,"text":"because they have to see so many children."},{"time":1027690,"text":"And we want to do that universally\nso that we don't miss any child."},{"time":1031791,"text":"But this would be immoral"},{"time":1034529,"text":"if we also did not have an infrastructure\nfor intervention, for treatment."},{"time":1040487,"text":"We need to be able to work\nwith the families, support the families,"},{"time":1044403,"text":"to manage those first years with them."},{"time":1048384,"text":"We need to be able to really go"},{"time":1050806,"text":"from universal screening\nto universal access to treatment,"},{"time":1054752,"text":"because those treatments\nare going to change"},{"time":1057765,"text":"these children's\nand those families' lives."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1062450,"text":"Now, when we think about what we [can]\ndo in those first years,"},{"time":1068912,"text":"I can tell you, having been\nin this field for so long,"},{"time":1074077,"text":"one feels really rejuvenated."},{"time":1076832,"text":"There is a sense that the science\nthat one worked on"},{"time":1081578,"text":"can actually have an impact on realities,"},{"time":1084371,"text":"preventing, in fact, those experiences"},{"time":1087972,"text":"that I really started\nin my journey in this field."},{"time":1091343,"text":"I thought at the time\nthat this was an intractable condition."},{"time":1094777,"text":"No longer. We can do\na great deal of things."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1098707,"text":"And the idea is not to cure autism."},{"time":1101140,"text":"That's not the idea."},{"time":1103791,"text":"What we want is to make sure"},{"time":1105889,"text":"that those individuals\nwith autism can be free"},{"time":1108465,"text":"from the devastating consequences\nthat come with it at times,"},{"time":1112876,"text":"the profound intellectual disabilities,\nthe lack of language,"},{"time":1115961,"text":"the profound, profound isolation."},{"time":1119563,"text":"We feel that individuals\nwith autism, in fact,"},{"time":1121833,"text":"have a very special\nperspective on the world,"},{"time":1124323,"text":"and we need diversity."},{"time":1126440,"text":"And they can work extremely well\nin some areas of strength:"},{"time":1130090,"text":"predictable situations,\nsituations that can be defined."},{"time":1133493,"text":"Because after all,\nthey learn about the world"},{"time":1136475,"text":"almost, like, about it,"},{"time":1138381,"text":"rather than learning\nhow to function in it."},{"time":1141202,"text":"But this is a strength if you're working,\nfor example, in technology."},{"time":1146081,"text":"And there are those individuals\nwho have incredible artistic abilities."},{"time":1149936,"text":"We want them to be free to do that."},{"time":1152293,"text":"We want that the next generations\nof individuals with autism"},{"time":1155436,"text":"will be able not only\nto express their strengths,"},{"time":1158538,"text":"but to fulfill their promise."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1160952,"text":"Well, thank you for listening to me."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1162723,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}